A Republican strategy to counter Obama&#39;s re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight against electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center regards the latter as a myth, claiming that voter fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Moreover, Republican lawyers have identified only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative influence on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, US states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of American governments promulgated from 2009 new laws making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to show photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce the periods for advance voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and deprive citizens with a criminal record of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no US state required voters to show photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The US Supreme Court upheld the Indiana law in 2008.
Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to show photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a state government agency.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18-29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, voters seen as voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their institution-issued photo IDs.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are US citizens.
These measures are clearly intended to limit the Hispanic vote.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
Separately, Republican lawmakers in 2011 sponsored laws abolishing Election Day voter registration in eight states.
In addition, they restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
Additionally, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance polls were African Americans, while African Americans made up only 13% of voters in the state.
The same was true with Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, the whites who formed 76% of the voters represented only 46% of the voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes from Democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has stepped in to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have laws requiring the presentation of photo ID.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undeniably make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see them as an obvious objective to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed for the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Screening for prostate cancer: to pass the test or not?
Indeed, the PSA test would sometimes present erroneous results, with false negative results or even false positives, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This is enough to make men who are already reluctant to take screening tests even more hesitant.
Pass the test or not?
We asked the opinion of two specialists.
In the studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between the control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, this one European, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had screening and those who had not.
This study also demonstrated, with a follow-up after 12 years, that we have between 30 and 40% more chances of having metastases if we are not screened.
I therefore recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at higher risk.
The key is to make the right decision once you have detected cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
You really have to make the patient understand the degree of risk of their cancer, by offering them the possible options, by not necessarily treating the prostate cancers that are not life-threatening in the long term, and by opting instead, in such cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and not life threatening.
We will suggest that they do active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we will offer them treatment.
More and more, precise criteria are being determined to decide who should or should not be treated.
So I still recommend taking the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine whether you should have it or not.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has created a tool that assesses the pros and cons of the PSA test.
