The Higgs boson dissected
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
Besides, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or &quot;least worst&quot; explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed. empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely sure that it is indeed the Higgs.
We know beyond a shadow of a doubt that we have a genuine new particle, and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be completely certain.
Suppose all the same that it is indeed the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and let&#39;s see what it is.
There is, in this world, a fatally inescapable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don&#39;t try too hard, you&#39;ll hurt yourself.
But even if particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it too has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same &quot;quantum state&quot; - this &quot;state&quot; roughly consisting of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli&#39;s principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a filthy bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means they may well be in the same place , at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, from Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the &quot;force particles&quot;, by which the great forces of nature are propagating and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not all such exotic critters as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon, or the &quot;particle of light&quot; which is the &quot;messenger&quot; of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it &quot;disturbs&quot; the electromagnetic field in that precise place, a bit like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this &quot;disturbance&quot; is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing other than a photon - and therefore, one of the force-carrying bosons.
More stable field
It is the same with the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be &quot;disturbed&quot; for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond whose surface only a very large rock could ripple.
That&#39;s why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is indeed not all the particles, nor all the materials, which interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but some don&#39;t - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold up on a fridge on its own.
And similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the others (like the photon, well) don&#39;t.
Now, what can all this research &quot;contribute&quot;, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this serves to check the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and predictions of the SM.
They are moreover several to ardently wish that we find some, because the slightest difference could open a door on a &quot;new physics&quot; and plug some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter in the Universe (oops again!) .
But no such discrepancies have been found at CERN so far.
Implications
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. Everybody are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will not be any.
Look: at the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories had no idea of the revolution that their work was about to trigger.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle once told us - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed), by 1962 -, initially the laser was seen more as a &quot;lab gadget&quot;.
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original intention, now serves as the &quot;eye&quot; of all digital cameras in the world, and won it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die... | The duty
With its Dying with Dignity Commission, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
Debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, in this essential area, much remains to be done.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look.
Barely a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was gnawing at him had given him a respite for two years.
“They gave me five years to live, I did seven years,” he says, half fig half grape, lying in bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he is. arrived the day before.
&quot;But it&#39;s always a shock, you can&#39;t be prepared for that,&quot; he said.
The disease does its work: an enormous weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even from eating alone.
Seated in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers who bustle around him, bring him his medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
&quot;My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it&#39;s humiliating,&quot; he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
“During our life, we learn that a man pees standing up,” says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
To regress to the stage of childhood, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the capacity of the person” to accept the regression, he notes.
Because, in the opinion of many people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
The patients who come to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life prognosis of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called &quot;curative&quot; care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die &quot;conscious and suffocated&quot;.
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
&quot;I have no more wishes in life,&quot; she said, before agreeing to have a mask put on her to help her breathe.
She is still expecting, in the coming days, a last visit from her son who has come from Italy.
At Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, we provide body care and food assistance.
This is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It&#39;s very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the house doctors.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
To the dying, we will agree to provide mouth care with brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, a beer was served to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days go by but are not alike.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who is enjoying his last family gathering in the yard, snuggled up in his pillows while we toast in his honor, a 36-year-old young man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, of his wife and two young children, after having tried everything to survive.
“For six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Maison Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is to say care designed to ease the suffering when a patient has reached the end of his life, whether either at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Maison Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Palliative Home Care of Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this major deficiency in Quebec health care that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by luminaries of palliative care including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before they agree to proceed with euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without anything being done to relieve her.
I fear that patients only ask to die because they do not receive adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists work hard on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognoses.
Hélène Richard&#39;s hopes of survival were already minimal when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
However, she had told me that I was finished!
Not almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not granting their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Palliative Home Care Society, patients are refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors then often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to putting the patient to sleep until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the possibility of having this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved always say the same sentence: &quot;I want to die.&quot;
But that doesn&#39;t necessarily mean &quot;I want you to euthanize me&quot;, it means &quot;I want to be relieved&quot;.
