About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today to around ten dollars (the prices are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to world trade in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes bitcoin as &quot;the most successful virtual currency&quot;, &quot;competing with the dollar or the euro&quot; and &quot;similar to conventional currencies&quot;.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as &quot;credits&quot;, used to progress in a video game that is earned by playing or can be purchased (and sometimes traded back).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both bookkeepers, verifiers, issuers of currency, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually between two electronic addresses in the manner of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged exist in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It passes by the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to the computers, and whose winner, sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add this additional line.
This is a file hash phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital fingerprint.
The computers &quot;take&quot; the new transaction and add a number to it before &quot;hashing&quot; the whole thing.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular fingerprint (lots of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number has been found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the correct one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the hundred millionth, which leaves room...
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoin deposits stolen.
&quot;The flaw used does not concern the protocol itself&quot;, assures Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a payment company in real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash also has this defect.
Major players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the blogging platform WordPress, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, &quot;giant sales&quot; were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are therefore cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is communicate an address that a telephone can &quot;photograph and recognize&quot;, specifies Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“Bitcoin will take time to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in the event of the success of this currency.
We left from Afghanistan.
And after ?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans should follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain possession of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting everything from us.
It is above all the Afghan peasants that we have punished by considering them to be terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former chiefs who have taken refuge in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in the days of the Soviets.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes helped by the local insurgents, these will no longer be so when the Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the Nijrab base, which I observed from the top of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was done in order.
The convoys of trucks and armored vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked, hovered over by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban surge in Kabul from the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country in fire and blood because of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country had then been perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghan women paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants overwhelmed by the organization of Al-Qaeda, but their situation has not improved these days.
Former mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban come together in the desire to keep women in an inferior position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have turned into wheeler-dealers, seizing government land to resell it as building land to refugees returning from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge American subcontracts.
They have discredited themselves; most of them did not fight themselves.
The people, as I have heard in the countryside, yearn for a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have taken advantage of American largesse: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They rubbed shoulders with the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan, they appreciated its advantages.
About 65% of the population is under 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, a fifth of the total population.
In the cities, the government schools are full, of girls as well as boys.
It will be necessary to provide work for these young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties nor to the corruption of certain leaders.
All, including armed opponents, are fond of mobile phones; television, and its Turkish serials which present a modern world, is followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who will order it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already preoccupied with reconstituting provincial militias, which will escape the central power.
Afghanistan, a country of mountains, with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from a certain decentralization, like Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state, with strong presidential power, eliminating the post of Prime Minister which had existed since the Constitution of 1964.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially in the run-up to elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has been, since the 1950s and long before, dependent on foreign aid.
No industry has been restarted, no dam is in working order, no major irrigation system has been repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced, except fruits and vegetables.
Priority is left to private initiative.
In a country ruined by thirty years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
It was rumored that Afghanistan had immense mineral wealth.
It only added to the feeling that Westerners were just there to grab it.
Without energy to process the iron or copper ore on site, or means of transport to export it across the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to excavate the huge Buddhist site and remain the province&#39;s largest employers.
It will also be necessary one day for Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports largely depend, to restore normal relations.
The departure of the French combat troops was completed on November 20.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aid: high school for girls and boys, French department at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to &quot;win hearts and minds&quot; and carry out the impossible task of matching aid and offensive actions, a &quot;civil-military actions&quot; service of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012 , has carried out, and had carried out by a small French NGO, numerous works of collective interest and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, greedy in local labor, were able to help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase in cultivable areas.
What will we leave behind, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to improving local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, often located at more than 2,000 meters in altitude.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural projects from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurrection led by foreign groups, which the farmers have told me they want, there should be a small amount of well-controlled civilian aid that affects them directly.
A Forceps Constitution in Egypt
It&#39;s a new gamble by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants him full powers, he has decided to gamble.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this Assembly two additional months to complete its work.
For nearly two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his &quot;autocratic delirium&quot;, continuing to &quot;betray his word&quot; and &quot;trample on the law&quot;.
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way of ending the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be organized within fifteen days.
A very short lapse of time which obliges the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while protests are raging throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this recourse to a hasty vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: &quot;Either you vote for my text, or I keep full powers&quot;, these should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, substitute members, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, most articles were voted on unanimously.
Commentators were also amused by the fact that one of the only divergences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, certain members of the committee considering that the pendulum of the constituent was badly regulated.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, comprises 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, article 2 ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that &quot;the principles of Sharia are the main source of law.&quot;
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace &quot;the principles&quot; by &quot;the rules&quot;, which would have allowed a stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a sign of their goodwill and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy”, answer the liberals, who see it only as a communication stunt.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They notably target Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because &quot;the people called upon to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see there the beginnings of a theocracy.
Liberal fears are further stoked by the fact that the next rector of this university should be far less moderate than the current one.
&quot;For the time being, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulema but academics, some trained in the French system&quot; tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes &quot;that there may be an ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
Reference is made there to &quot;fiqh&quot; in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, editor&#39;s note].
And the question could in the future arise as to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on it&quot;.
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argue that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: the powers granted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the Defense budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defense Council.
Nor will the trials of civilians in military tribunals be prohibited, as demanded by associations for the defense of human rights.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticidal.
The offense of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly of the press.
In addition, no article echoes the protection of women more, underlines Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Supporters of the Head of State will parade on Saturday.
In Israel, holy sites, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comforts and a wilderness.
Argoumenty i Fakty has identified five main reasons for visiting Israel.
Go worship the holy places
Must-see: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that whoever enters these &quot;baptismal fonts&quot; will be touched by divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of Jesus&#39; miracles: where the water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where fishing was miraculous.
It is at this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk the Rue de la Souffrance or the Stations of the Cross (in Latin: the Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia Fortress (praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher on Golgotha, towards the place of the Crucifixion , then to that of the Stone of Anointing and the Entombment.
Here is the Christian center of the world, symbol of the salvation of mankind.
According to Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is erected on the spot where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place for the Jews: the Wailing Wall which is the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC. JC.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave little notes there accompanied by prayers which are then answered.
Travel high
Visit the ruins of the Masada fortress, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC. JC. for her family.
These ruins are on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs hold that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
Impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are definitely worth a look.
First up: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran Scrolls, or Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also worth seeing: the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
Mainly exhibited are paintings by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths made up of casts of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which revisits the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the Children&#39;s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and step into total darkness.
Stars twinkle.
You then hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
health and wellbeing
Israel&#39;s three major resorts are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the temperature of the water does not drop below 21° while that of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, this is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth - 417 m below sea level.
The azure colored water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are of surreal beauty.
People come here to carry out a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative muds and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the edge of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow streets named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to &quot;your&quot; sign, fate will smile on you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come for photo shoots from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, &quot;conquer&quot; the Crusader fortress.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you are going to Israel, don&#39;t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to euros, since they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equal to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city. .
It is almost an underground funicular.
The trip on all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop operating.
And the working week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels only serve kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and mixed milk and meat dishes.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts made with coconut milk, but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, balls of ground chickpeas, falafels, Fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk around looking haughty.
They can be seen in the evening sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
These felines love busy places and do not refuse to be treated.
Renting a car varies by brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Admission to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
&quot;Who language has, in Moscow goes&quot;: migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists argue over what the mandatory language test law will do, scammers selling &#39;fake&#39; certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families at home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force stipulating that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian language exam.
At this time, this rule only affects those who intend to work in the service, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the History of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will have to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of an official language are exempt.
People who obtained teaching certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Profit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, Peoples&#39; Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly posed the question in the press: what will happen?
What will the requirement to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, say the representatives of the migration service, it will reduce the number of people suffering from &quot;work slavery&quot;.
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, certifies Sebelev, the future migrant is destined to come across dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a &quot;trip&quot; to an overcrowded cottage where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and without paper and will have to toil between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
&quot;At home, we promise them one thing, and when they arrive, we deceive them, we take their passport, and they do not receive the expected salary&quot;, confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of the Migration Service from Tajikistan, Tolib Charipov.
Don&#39;t argue with me, policeman!
However, many nationals of the Central Asian republics who wish to come and earn money in Russia confide that they not only do not know the language of the country where they wish to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children let alone dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It&#39;s difficult when you don&#39;t know the language, they say.
&quot;You feel diminished and belittled.&quot;
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be intended only for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no exam or official work afterwards.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
&quot;Welcome or no entry&quot;
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain an official status in Russia.
The reason? The administrative barriers and always these linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
And then one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we have no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
&quot;They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, enough to buy cigarettes, tea,&quot; Oumed Khouchkadamov, a national of Tajikistan, told reporters.
&quot;Hurry up, don&#39;t skimp and buy yourself a beautiful piece of art&quot;
From the first day of the entry into force of the law relating to the language, it was discovered that the registration papers of the migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Forged papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not get them for nothing: each migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of examinations in this way had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: the latter will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power officials and human rights advocates agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system against corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these &quot;pieces of paper&quot;.
The authorities can give migrant workers who were unable to pass the exam on the first try time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in fields that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to toughen the law against carriers of civilian weapons.
Such is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings carried out at weddings or the massacre organized by the Muscovite lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which left seven dead.
Police want to ban the carrying of rubber bullet guns in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun license from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma committee for security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya who promised that the amendments to the law on weapons would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by &quot;tightening the screw&quot;.
An open letter has appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon &quot;this senseless hardening&quot;.
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime expert for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168,000 crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that tougher civilian gun laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing on the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the distribution of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from the factory to the officer
The black market for weapons is supplied through several channels.
The main canals are five in number, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years at the Ministry of Education and at Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking orders for weapons
The first is &quot;the military trace&quot;, that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
&quot;These weapons were stolen by the Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians&quot;, explains Baranets.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of these often suffered explosions.
&quot;Attested versions indicate that some fires were set on purpose to conceal the deficit,&quot; explains the former soldier.
For Baranets, the arms manufacturers have something to do with it.
&quot;We see private arms factories that do not compete with the competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,&quot; says an expert.
Another source of the black market is contraband.
A significant share of pistols and submachine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
&quot;There is local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply,&quot; adds the former soldier.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts have estimated each source&#39;s approximate share of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was compiled in 2011 by the Center for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement agencies.
Half of the weapons present on the black market ended up there &quot;through the fault of the employees whose work is related to the weapons&quot;, explains one in the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from the places of military conflicts, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% come from &quot;clandestine excavations&quot;.
A salesman and consultant from an armory who asked to remain anonymous assures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine excavation specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers pick up new goods from military warehouses.
