It is for the moment difficult to say if this spark of mass movement will make children.
&quot;For the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain&quot;
Lately, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November we learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it appears from the interview with the director of the group of interactive 3D technologies of the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, that for the scientists of this company, the glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group does?
- We work on the interaction between man and machine and we try at the same time to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has remained for the moment with pixels on flat screens and sometimes with touch.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead of us and guess what drastic changes will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox is sold today without Kinect because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What does the future also hold for us?
- Although the Kinect made the interaction physical, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has been improved (the system receives more data), but the output, for the moment, not really.
We&#39;re trying to change that and we&#39;re working on true 3D imaging systems that run on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We have to bring the computer world out into ours, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space around him.
Thus, we will be able to complete the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And for starters, let&#39;s get rid of those stupid VR headsets!
- What do you think of the voice command?
She is appreciated, but isn&#39;t she overrated?
We cannot say that this is a panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because we do not always want to inform others of our actions or our intentions.
In fact, every type of computer interaction is good, but each in its own niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not large gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures weren&#39;t captured by the device&#39;s camera, but by a hand-worn wristband that recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- That&#39;s to say?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can?
You would do it with speech and with gestures.
- Usually, I only talk.
- Oh, that&#39;s going to be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or cannot do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
It can be for example laser sensors, they produce a fairly good depth resolution and this is very important.
- If we&#39;re interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what don&#39;t you like about modern cameras?
They lack resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we base our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be nice to get around 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but rather the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all the current technologies are quite good, it adds work to the designers of algorithms.
You have to keep in mind the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the 30 c / s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche from our Redmond lab has given sensors touch a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 µs, with current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would really need a device of this type in my work, but not requiring touch, to have more frames per second.
- But shouldn&#39;t the number of cameras be increased?
- The Kinect now has three &quot;cameras&quot;, one of which is in fact an infrared transmitter and the second, a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a regular visible field sensor.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
Many cameras could solve this problem...
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to the Kinect, to play with the curve of the cameras and see how that could help define the locations.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not introduce its glasses to the public.
Don&#39;t you think that from the point of view of daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the platforms with the most prospects?
- Of course, walking around all the time with a smartphone with your hands up is not practical, but here&#39;s what I think: the best option would be a &quot;transitional&quot; augmented reality that would allow you from a cloud platform to pass glasses to smartphone.
The glasses are a very personal device and that is their strength (the personal elements are the ones you are the only one to see) and at the same time their weakness: the augmented reality from the glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
- Let&#39;s imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to ordinary mortals.
There is one problem that opponents of this idea point their finger at: there is no tactile sensation!
Hands feel nothing!
What responses is your group preparing to this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
At the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to act as an image carrier.
It registers the pressures perfectly!
But there are also technologies which are really intended to give palpability to these &quot;images in the air&quot;: for example the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a precise point where the finger is and which gives you the sensation, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of the fingers.
There are also the bracelets worn on the wrists which influence the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a line of work presenting perspectives.
- And you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think he feels what he should normally feel when he sees something?
- That&#39;s a good idea, we haven&#39;t tried it yet.
There is still a task below which we will have to work hard for a long time yet: how to make someone who is physically in a very small space believe that he is walking in an almost infinite open space - we working on the concepts of treadmills (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
For the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain, there are still many years of work.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in an absolute state of fertilization.
