This is a parallel control that we started about two years ago.
In simple terms, EU law sets out how public procurement should be handled, and specific national laws and practice follow.
We have put all this together and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, some very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation is perhaps &quot;tougher and better&quot;, nevertheless, according to certain parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This therefore confirms that it is not enough to continually develop more and more detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote oneself to the actual application of the law.
How can this project help you concretely and what does it mean for you?
A common control of this type should precisely help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering the market thresholds, we will not necessarily achieve this objective.
It could be that this system is so overwhelmed with paperwork that those looking for loopholes will find many more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You talk about internal problems concerning the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our SAI or a different mode of organization?
As far as institutions are concerned, like the ISC, the Bundesrechnungshof works there, which is organized similarly, it also has a council constituted a little differently, but these two institutions basically operate in a similar way.
The competences are also, to a certain extent, similar, with one nuance, however, in relation to our system: Germany being a federal structure, it therefore also has courts of auditors of this type at the level of the various Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which in our country corresponds to state resources.
The public funds managed here by the regions and municipalities are controlled there by the courts of auditors of the Länder.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, nevertheless, in certain areas, Germany is often pointed out as a model but we cannot surely say that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it&#39;s because they have better inspectors?
No, definitely not, but again, I don&#39;t have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country that we consider as a model is also facing a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage in cooperating with our institution, right?
With regard to national legislation, what has the amendment of the law on public procurement meant for you as an institution, are its effects already being felt?
As this amendment entered into force relatively recently, it has not yet had an impact on our control operations.
As we carry out checks a posteriori, it is necessary to count with a certain delay.
Our observations relate only, for the moment, to the process of preparing for future controls - we have launched a new instrument for &quot;detection of the risks of mismanagement&quot; with which we have screened almost 14,000 public contracts - there these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been changed as well as the conditions for certain types of tendering procedures and so on.
So do you consider the adoption of this law rather as an advantage or as an additional burden for the administration?
I think this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more severe and it is not possible to respect them.
Already under the previous regulations, the service provider (for example the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the subjects audited to accept that any violation of the law on contracts means a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really useful to make the law tougher in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse it, but not punish those who make formal errors that have no consequence on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let&#39;s see where we&#39;re not going.
Recently, the prime minister said that the ODS is not going to bother entrepreneurs with checks from the so-called Švarc system - what does this mean?
Is the Švarc system prohibited or authorized?
The law must be enforced one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going to inspect and demand compliance with the law. .
He can say, &quot;We&#39;re going to change the law and allow it,&quot; but he can&#39;t say we&#39;re going to act like nothing happened.
The procurement law includes relatively strict rules on the formalities to be completed, precisely in order to protect the call for tenders.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and that, in my opinion, is what is lacking here.
The roads are frozen in places, but most remain passable.
In some places in the Czech Republic, the roads are frozen and also snowy.
However, the network remains for the most part practicable, in certain places with increased vigilance.
Karlovy Vary region
In the Karlovy Vary region, the roads were passable this morning, but in places frozen and also snowy.
Temperatures have dropped and fluctuate between -5° and -10° C but they should rise slightly during the day.
Snowfall has ceased in the region and only a light dusting of snow remains on the plains.
The ridges of the Ore Mountains (Krušné hory) are however covered with about 30 centimeters of snow.
Data from the regional road maintenance service show that due to the fog, visibility was reduced in places.
The R6 expressway and the national roads of the region are now passable without difficulty.
However, vigilance is still required, for example on certain bridges where the surface can be frozen and slippery.
All county roads and third category roads, including mountain roads, are also passable.
There are still remnants of frozen snow on some of their sections and in places packed down by traffic.
Especially in areas located at high altitudes, drivers must increase their vigilance.
Pardubice and Hradec Králové regions
