Šimon Ornest said: &quot;In concert, we want to collect positive energy.&quot;
What do you think of the fact that in less than a month it should be the end of the world?
This is just one of those alarming news, the kind of traps we like to fall into.
In our group The Tap Tap, we rather laugh about it and we say to ourselves that we are the only group capable of collecting a rest of positive energy in order to postpone or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December you are putting together a very unique project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you present this project in more detail to our readers?
It is a charitable action that we have been preparing for two years already.
We decided to use the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 am.
The day before, December 20, three concerts will take place simultaneously, in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end almost at the end of the Mayan calendar on the island of Kiribati, which is in the Pacific Ocean, on a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who had this idea?
At first I think it was my idea, then we designed everything with our creator, Honza Augusta.
Apart from the fact that we want to collect enough positive energy to save the world, we also want together with the public to reflect on the state of the world that we leave to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have created a collection of unique objects, including shoes, T-shirts, bags, and original keys against the end of the world, by purchasing them online at www.e -tap.cz people can also support us.
The group The Tap Tap with other performers has also recorded a hymn against the end of the world which is called &quot;End of the world cancelled&quot; (in Czech &quot;Konec světa zrušeno&quot;).
She is already very popular on YouTube, will we also hear her during these charity concerts?
Of course, at the very end, well, if we succeed and the end of the world does not take place...
It will be sung simultaneously by all the performers in the three concerts.
The anthems will also come together at some point in a very unique live broadcast on Czech television.
The lyrics of this song were written by Tomáš Hanák who also plays the main role of Jesus in the clip, Xindl X also sings there...
How did you come to cooperate with them?
We collaborate with other Czech showbiz personalities, due to the fact that we organize many concerts and charity events...
We strive to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in such cooperation and enjoy it.
What will the benefits of these concerts against the end of the world be used for?
To equip the Studeo training center which is accessible to people with reduced mobility and which we have been working on within the framework of the Jedlička institute, with the Tap association, and that for six years.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedličkův Institute and offer them activities that interest and amuse them.
The students themselves cannot afford to go to classes, we try to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the construction of the Jedlička Institute, we will transfer this project to a new independent building.
Several music groups and performers will take the stage during each of these concerts?
According to what criteria did you choose them?
We have tried to develop a program that speaks to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will take the stage.
Full details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you also preparing for other such &quot;mega events&quot; in the future?
In May we will play for the first time as part of the Prague Spring; there too, we will surely prepare a quality program with interesting guests.
We would also like to play next year in the house of the Czech Republic in New York and personally, once there in the United States, I would like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is nevertheless a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It&#39;s not as terrible as it looks at first glance.
We have five members in electric wheelchairs whose machines have to travel in the hold, naturally we also carry around a lot of luggage and boxes of instruments....
So far everything has more or less always gone well, ČSA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to your travels abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of ease of access for people with reduced mobility, the attitude of public opinion towards people with disabilities and so on. right now.
What have your experiences been so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have just witnessed in Moscow that in the east everything is still only in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very inaccessible to people with disabilities; there, it is not yet common for a person to travel alone in an electric wheelchair in the center of the city.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association trying to draw attention to the problems of disabled people is being created.
How do we still have to catch up with more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we are still late for...
It is important to mention that improvements and refinements always depend on the efforts made by the people concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move about alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
It&#39;s not very common over there that a large number of disabled people actively participate in social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather on the contrary at the forefront of progress!
Public respect and ease of access are one thing, but the situation will really begin to change when we have among us famous sportsmen, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers.
At the moment, these are just isolated cases of people who are strong-willed.
The group The Tap Tap is currently very popular, let&#39;s go back a few years, what pushed you in 1998 to create this group?
I started working as an educator at the Jedlička Institute, where I found myself surrounded by a lot of young people ready to get involved in something.
And since I am a musician myself (I play the saxophone, among other things), with a colleague, we have created a music activity.
And then, over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, we lost control of the situation a bit (laughs).
Success only happened in the last few years, if I&#39;m not mistaken?
It&#39;s true, bonding with well-known singers and actively working to promote the band has helped us.
We have understood that, if a work is not visible, it is as if it did not exist in the background.
Thanks to subsidies from the European Union, we can also afford to have quality teachers, equipment, and so on.
Did you aim to reach such a level with The Tap Tap?
Right from the start, I felt there was potential to change things.
Show business is full of tricks that copy each other.
In a way, it makes sense: everything new is accepted with caution and it lasts a long time.
Original projects are rare, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is naturally pity, it&#39;s natural...
But pity is totally useless, because people with disabilities are not suffering beings, abandoned by everyone, whom we should pity.
These are people who can live a full life and flourish, provided they have the necessary means of course.
I often say that when people with disabilities manage to achieve something, it&#39;s not only a step forward for them but for the whole society.
Isn&#39;t your success also due to the fact that you are a demanding leader, as you are qualified by many people?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be intransigent in many areas and demand a certain discipline.
But I think it&#39;s completely normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds and, when they realize that they have to come to rehearsals twice a week, take preparatory classes and spend a lot of time on the road for concerts, they quickly lose their enthusiasm.
But it works the same way in every group that wants to work and achieve goals.
The group The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them were already there in 1998?
Only one, Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people come and go, there&#39;s nothing we can do about it.
Our doors are always open to those who want or would like to join us.
