Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, during the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Republic Czech became a full member on November 12, 2008).
Poland entered into close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of the agency&#39;s projects.
Poland&#39;s road to space, however, began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. Šternfeld&#39;s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933, during which he presented ideas taken from his avant-garde work entitled &quot;Introduction to Astronautics&quot;.
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only doctor Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld obtained in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his work &quot;Introduction to astronautics&quot;.
The said doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) subsequently became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote numerous books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-famous propagator of astronautics, his contribution was notably rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the far side of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a handcar was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the draisine.
The only known information on this draisine is that of the press of the time.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the documents preserved that this research had reached the trial stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work &quot;Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza&quot; by an author named Leliwy was published. -Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were aimed at the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (&quot;Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy&quot;), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of operation, the outbreak of the war put an end to its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronautics
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and by autumn the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the international astronautical federation.
He retained his position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the RM-2 two-stage rocket were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been capable of carrying out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and served for observing the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first rockets of the RM type.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters, and in Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a 10 kg payload to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland&#39;s entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites, and in 1978 pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut in this program.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Utility Works Act.
This decision aroused a lively discussion in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to examine this problem from a broader point of view.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means concretely that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and the free circulation (without limits) of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
Considerable differences in the price of labor (wages) generate pressure on prices.
This term should have the following meaning: a producer endeavors by importing goods sold at a low price to resist economic competition by &quot;making the competitor&#39;s price more expensive&quot;, with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either moving production abroad, or buying cheap, or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social charges of the state necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so common knowledge that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without regard to social collapse.
This manifests itself mainly in the amendments of the laws in force.
The objective is to force its own population economically to accept the diktat of the prices of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This occurs on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other hand by the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labor legislation.
The result is growing poverty and the deepening of the differences between rich and poor.
In the FRG, for years there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own labour.
There are already millions of such people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a supplement for them to reach the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal has, for example, been brought to light in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economy measures of virtually all southern EU Member States are undoubtedly generating a similar situation in which, under the pressure of catastrophic societal breakdown, people are forced either to emigrate ( as was the case in the 19th century), or to scrape by on starvation wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
The following question must be asked here: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or else a Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also concerns all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim, wearily, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the command economy leads to economic catastrophe.
Private capital fiercely defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and even direct today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and, by the same token, the entire state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby present in all states.
The result is a hopeless situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, by the granting of mutual advantages, in the legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the FRG, the situation is such that, due to a lack of financial means, the national ministries delegate the drafting of bills to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is obvious that the democracies oriented towards liberalism are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his work entitled &quot;the crisis of the Roman Empire in the time of Caesar and Pompey&quot;: &quot;The State had long been in full decay and the functions were attributed by violence.
Kickbacks, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to secure these positions.
Kickbacks and corruption proliferated without limit and the people went to the elections with votes already sold &quot;... ... &quot; Honest people did not seek any office, it resulted once that the State remained 8 months without consuls&quot;.... &#39; People really began to say that the remedy for this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man&quot;... It is true that Appianos had to Pompey&#39;s spirit, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, today&#39;s society is based on the preference for personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and advance the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of things, we can consider the disappearance of these systems in favor of liberal-type democracies as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future losses in human life, the humanitarian and social crises that we are witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and internally in Europe, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to lower the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is sociopolitical reforms that will strengthen state capital investment in the economy, increase citizens&#39; influence over government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society to the benefit of society. &#39;State.
