The Argo Movie: When It&#39;s Bad, Call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrators made up of Islamist students stormed the American embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who after the revolution had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was unable to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow made worse later by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their plight sparked an outpouring of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle was a major contributor to Jimmy Carter&#39;s defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode in this history that offered a small victory for America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated adventures, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to an incredible cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who had come to scout locations for the filming of a sci-fi spectacle film.
Combination of genres
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez&#39;s plan required Hollywood collaboration.
In order to make the legend more believable, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck&#39;s film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is partly a realistic political thriller, but also a &quot;caper movie&quot;, the story of a successful coup, a treachery - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean&#39;s eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres follow one another: sequences of Tehran in documentary style (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs from the time of the events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes of CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in hallways and on the telephone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting ceased to elicit ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark detective &quot;Gone Baby Gone&quot; (2007) and the thriller &quot;The town&quot; (2010).
It is also Affleck&#39;s first film not set in his hometown of Boston.
A sense of the atmosphere of a location is one of the characteristics that set his early films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Tehran&#39;s role is &quot;held&quot; by Canada.
The film&#39;s best scenes take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real events; the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to make do with a subject that actually offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
He comes out of it very well, he sometimes adds certain elements to reality and there, the result is not always so elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America and the chase on the airstrip are pretty far-fetched).
Argo&#39;s weakness lies in its dissipated nature, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role of Hollywood co-operators, their characters deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck&#39;s film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it lets itself be seen with moderate interest, enjoying the direction and the retro style of the 70s.
He leads the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in some ways, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the portrayal of the Secret Service as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the trick.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and the circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a public survey on the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch a competition for the most absurd regulations or ideas from the &quot;EU workshop&quot; .
&quot;The fact that the EU recently considered adopting a 40 percent quota for women in the management of large European companies was the reason for our decision,&quot; said the newspaper Právo l organizer of this survey, Patrik Nacher.
Among the absurdities mentioned there is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women have had an advantage in terms of life insurance rates because they represent, objectively, a lower risk for insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such amazing idea of &quot;EU workshop&quot;.
“The vote will take place before the end of February 2013,” Nacher informed.
Among the controversial EU regulations are, for example, the obligation to add bio-components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance or the directive on the size of hen cages, which has led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticism has also been leveled in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term &quot;spreadable butter&quot; or the removal of conventional light bulbs from sale.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a State or a group of States (thus the Czech Republic currently imposes the demands of its banks by threatening to use his right of veto).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, behind the fact that in the Union bananas must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an &quot;abnormal curvature&quot;.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was only harmonizing non-homogeneous national standards which complicated trade.
Fruit and vegetable standards have been relaxed despite opposition from some states, claiming the existing guidelines result in food waste.
Perhaps the top prize in this survey will go to last year&#39;s EU regulation that inflatable balls must bear a warning that children under the age of 8 should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU referred to a US survey that found balloons to be the number one cause of child suffocation deaths among toys.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when it comes to blowing fairground trumpets.
We also have bizarre ideas.
The following rule concerning European civil servants themselves is quite absurd: due to the sensitivity of this topic for Greece, anyone with an official function within the EU cannot use the name &quot;Macedonia&quot; and must, instead, talk about FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the &quot;Laissez Faire&quot; association of liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com has named in this investigation, in addition to some nonsense mentioned above, the Union&#39;s regulation regarding the volume of food reserves on the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for the reserves of food products that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volumes fixed for canned mushrooms and risked a heavy fine as a result.
The organizers of this survey considered the idea of paying sums of money to certain countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a subsidy to request the granting of subsidies.
These ideas, however, did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
“The fact of not having sea handicaps us.
We are going to ask the European Union for a refund&quot;. Thus expressed, in the autumn of 2004, the Minister of Agriculture at the time Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
He argued that, because of our wheat production, and following the so-called &quot;interventionist&quot; purchases, the State had found itself with full stocks which it had then had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech request and organized a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
Subsidies for obtaining subsidies were offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), these were, in concrete terms, to be used to write applications for subsidies granted by Brussels.
The EU says: &quot;weird regulations are rare&quot;.
While regulations often arouse criticism in the Member States, according to many experts, the efforts made by the EU in terms of regulation and improving the effectiveness of the functioning of the Union as well as in the field of its development general, rather deserve praise.
More serious is, for example, according to the experts, the problem of the use of EU subsidies for projects which have absolutely nothing to do with the strengthening of European integration, but which have been imposed by the Member States during budgetary negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other countries in the Union, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a fight from which it does not always emerge victorious) arouses strong feelings among the Czechs.
If after six years of battle against the Germans and the Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name &quot;Olomoucké tvarůžky&quot;, as for the name &quot;Tuzemský rum&quot; which dates back to us in the 19th century, our producers have had to replace it with the name &quot;Tuzemák&quot;.
Only products based on cane sugar alcohol, and not based on beet sugar, can bear the name of rum.
In the official list of registered products of the EU, one finds today, together with world-famous cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, Lübeck marzipan or Parma ham, biscuits from Karlovy Vary (&quot;Karlovarské suchary&quot; ), carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň (&quot;Pohořelický a Třeboňský kapr&quot;) and hops from Žatec (&quot;Žatecký chmel&quot;).
Pardubice gingerbread (&quot;Pardubický perník&quot;) and cakes called &quot;Cornets de Hořice&quot; (&quot;hořické trubičky&quot;) can also be proud of their community trademark.
People want me to save the Republic, but I&#39;m just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, how does one get the idea of standing for the presidential elections?
It&#39;s not being a senator or president that matters to me.
If everything worked smoothly in our country, I wouldn&#39;t be a candidate anywhere.
But I can&#39;t bear to see how the country has been plundered for the past twenty years, that the thieves are not locked up and the taxes and the retirement age are increasing.
I had no ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something that I don&#39;t like, then I try to bring a solution to change it.
And as I am over forty years old and I am independent, member of no party, I have no other solution to influence the situation than to present myself in the presidential or senatorial elections.
You entered the Senate but quickly made your way to the Castle.
Are you not thus turning your back on those who elected you?
I have always said that I will fight for the Castle according to the results of the senatorial elections.
Subsequently, I specified that if I were elected senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not the function, this one is only an instrument allowing me to realize my vision.
This is why I need the greatest influence and the broadest mandate.
