The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that real adventures are not only a matter of imagination. To be convinced of this, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
&quot;I think this building is funny, it looks very futuristic, finally something interesting to see&quot;, says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large neighboring company, tells us: &quot;Yes, it is indeed very beautiful, this building&quot;.
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes voluntarily into one of those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, an unattractive bedroom community on the outskirts of Rotterdam, holds a rather peculiar record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges which appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty little miniatures in reinforced concrete painted.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics: building a library!
Winy Maas, of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, a master of bold bar diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual composure and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under the arms and a sneer on his face.
And while the members of the jury still looked at each other, bewildered and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the cheeky one, piled his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments with a: &quot;dear commune!&quot;
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as we say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros has sprung up from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and terraced houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books received the second prize &quot;Best Library of NL 2012&quot;.
Furthermore, the project was shortlisted for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is how this dull little town, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a bewilderingly ugly town hall, whose white facades invite you to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese cover.
Admittedly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you set foot on the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The all-glass interior is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant lampposts speak unequivocally the language of municipal plazas.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library shelves are along the front and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” explains Willy Maas.
We have completely upset the classic spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skilfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A special beauty lies in the black shelves of the library, which are sometimes paneling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes banisters.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers don&#39;t want unfamiliar materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager with the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to Standard.
This is how one day we found in a Frisian agricultural company an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, one millimeter thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It&#39;s cheap and saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the &quot;Landbouwplastic&quot; (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes .
At the top of the 105 steps is the summit of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but above all they contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity in the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
&quot;It&#39;s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,&quot; says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell jar, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on sunny days.
The thick wooden beams mounted at an angle to the glass facade serve as a sun shield, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated awnings take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned skeptical computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as &quot;the soul finally found&quot; of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, during the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the gaps in the library which was not yet fully stocked (today it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays overflow from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, &quot;there is nothing worse than a half-empty library.&quot;
&quot;I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
