Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians&#39; request for observer state status at the United Nations.
But she then chose abstention.
For what?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin should exercise caution, as it has a special relationship with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being overly critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain during the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is in the process of reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a so to speak American-defined policy and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore came up against several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still groping to find this role, but are on the way to a &quot;more normal&quot; foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
So what does the term &quot;normal&quot; foreign policy actually mean for the Germans?
It shows the desire to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence Germany&#39;s stance on the Middle East conflict and abstention in the UN vote?
Germany first has major outlets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
This is why Berlin must be careful not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively one-sided relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Is Germany harming its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
This is why I think the divide is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected for it.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions regarding the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto in a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the domestic American political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
