Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I think that does not make things easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today this is not the case.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must assert their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the question of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will take on a leading role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It&#39;s not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been tricky.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they have to play a role which marks more their independence.
Does Germany see itself as a strong player on the international scene, does Germany just want to take on a key role?
