&quot;Brand protection&quot; in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name hides a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trademark thus enjoys such protection that the company that bears the name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, it is not certain that she would succeed.
“It is increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in infringement of property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Impersonators only need a few extra letters to be able to register their marks.
So, instead of Gucci, we register Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we register Prada-Kny.
German companies are also being copied quite legally, such as Puma, the sporting goods manufacturer.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet containing the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping centers that sell practically only counterfeits.
Pattloch&#39;s cases are different, however: his principals task him with challenging the fact that China&#39;s trademark office formally grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of &quot;Bang Mingpai&quot;, a parent brand.
The term is derived from &quot;Bang Dakuan&quot;.
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are designated.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to be ashamed of.
&quot;It&#39;s bad for business, we have to fight against this trend,&quot; demands Pattloch.
&quot;The brand is watered down, the uniqueness disappears, the reputational damage is enormous.&quot;
Financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the affected sectors, especially with regard to expensive flagships.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, China is the world&#39;s third-largest and fastest-growing luxury goods market with an annual volume of 15 billion euros.
However, it is not easy to remove questionable registrations from the Trademark Register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports on the lawsuits in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long period the criticized name had become a &quot;market reality&quot;.
Pattloch explains to us that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, because he would have damaged his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just taken over concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
This is the reason why the Chinese can use an emblem resembling the Mercedes star.
Geely, the acquirer of Volvo, previously used a blue and white logo reminiscent of that of BMW. The conflict was settled and Geely had to modify it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost against plagiarists from Hong Kong and Singapore who had redirected the gaze of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO Trademark Office in Beijing admits, however, that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office is said to have moved last year from an “emergency situation in the course of work to a newfound normality”.
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition procedures would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases are reported to have been closed, representing a 75% increase over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 procedures remain pending at the office.
Acting is expensive
As often in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and it means that China is for the tenth consecutive time at the top of the ranking for the number of new filings in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal marks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office would have recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each recording earned an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg illustrates.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarist.
True, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain his Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
&quot;It&#39;s our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,&quot; says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialties in Munich.
The trademark office had therefore rejected the objection of the Munich residents.
Freudenberg certainly won his case with the two following bodies, but the opposing party continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is key
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: &quot;the procedure is long, trying and costs us a lot of time and money.&quot;
It is also difficult to assess the internal costs. The archives service even had to review the records of the last hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg had even unsuccessfully offered the opposing party a &quot;large sum in six-figure euros&quot; to settle the dispute.
&quot;That&#39;s how we see what it means to us,&quot; says Wentzler.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to spill over into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from this region ensured the exploitation of unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to register the Freudenberg name in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but was still able to prevent the filing.
Wentzler adds: &quot;vigilance is in order&quot;.
He and Pattloch advise German companies to exercise great caution in their business dealings with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, rather foreigners should &quot;register also in China everything that is likely to be protected&quot;, as Wentzler puts it.
Otherwise, the costs can be much higher than the registration costs.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the final act of its legal drama, the company would have to pay licensing fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
