Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea often appear in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is the cause of at least four out of five reported cases of syphilis in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydial infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread between heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections occur among this group.
Among young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydial infections than among other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections occur in young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure rose from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been falling.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual disease?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white discharge, pain in the lower abdomen as well as the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they regularly cause no pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they don&#39;t provide 100% protection.
The reason for this is that the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or close bodily contact.
Experts therefore recommend that anyone who often changes sexual partners undergo regular examinations.
Most STIs detected early can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
