I&#39;m in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It&#39;s snowing, the scenery is spectacular - and that omnipresent smell permeates the air.
Rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on how you want it to smell - which can be up to a year.
When darkness sets in and the weather gets cold, Norwegians flock in droves to attend a festival held here in Fagernes dedicated to this incredible culinary delicacy.
“You eat raw, then you down a glass of aquavit,” says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter who is also known as “Rakfisk General”, responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people are swallowing small pieces of fish and drinking a large amount of drink.
