The drink kills the smell.
I try a few pieces.
If you can avoid having it pass under your nose, that&#39;s not bad - it&#39;s reminiscent of sushi that has been sitting for long hours on a bus.
Rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration the fish was immersed in airtight barrels of water and then salted in autumn.
Then, over the winter, once well fermented, the fish was taken out and - no doubt with the senses diminished by the alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, mainly emigrating to the United States.
