Bradley Manning has not complained of abuse, say prosecutors.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of abuse Bradley Manning allegedly suffered while in custody.
The lawsuit concerns Manning&#39;s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning&#39;s sequestration was carried out under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to show on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being the source of the biggest leak of confidential information in the history of the American military -- missed numerous opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
In cross-examination with Manning during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that records of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine months in custody in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
Cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defense brought a motion demanding that the Manning case be dismissed on the grounds that the forcible confinement was carried out under very difficult conditions and was a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified that he wanted to kill himself while in custody.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were later published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
During Friday&#39;s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms the officers filled out after meeting Manning while he was held in Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum solitary confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein discussed the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was &quot;excellent&quot; and that the treatment he received within the prison was &quot;very professional overall.&quot;
The forms do not list any complaints of mistreatment, although officers questioned him directly about his prison treatment, Fein claimed.
Manning replied that he had verbally expressed concerns about some issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues raised.
&quot;They wrote &#39;no issues&#39; (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn&#39;t mean I didn&#39;t raise issues,&quot; Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he hadn&#39;t complained about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months previously.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating &quot;risk of injury&quot;.
The military said they assigned him this restrictive status -- one level below close watch for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
&quot;I wanted the staff to know that I was okay, and I wanted to have that status taken away...to have a better quality of life from my perspective,&quot; Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at Marine Corps Base Quantico, Va., in July. 2010.
He said he contemplated suicide while in Kuwait and once passed out from the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
&quot;My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,&quot; Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 9 p.m. and sometimes more than 11 p.m. -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to keep moving, as sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also clarified that when he was trying to sleep he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn&#39;t see his face when he rolled over at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning&#39;s attorney filed a formal complaint for Manning&#39;s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about an allegation in his Thursday testimony -- that after he was forced to sleep naked all night in his cell at Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates one morning during roll call.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge&#39;s questioning on Friday, Manning said he inferred from his guard&#39;s order that he should let go of his blanket which might have concealed his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one ordered him to let go. .
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning allegedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his underpants or his flip flops to hurt himself, but he didn&#39;t.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip flops, and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will consider his experiences while in custody and significantly reduce his sentence should he be found guilty at a court martial, a trial that is expected to be held early in the year. &#39;next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the lesser offenses and fight to have other charges deemed too extreme committed.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with regulations that govern the conditions of confinement of all detainees at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy resulting in the unlawful publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defense.
If all charges are upheld, he faces life imprisonment.
