The Arab Spring shattered everything, and whether we like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify a little more.
Still, there&#39;s every reason to think it could help them out of this deadly stalemate.
A war that has no losers and no winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
Even if the ceasefire granted on November 21 holds, this week&#39;s fighting has strengthened supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to give up, even though Gaza has taken a beating.
Having killed some of its leaders and driven back the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza into one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel has not succeeded in destroying Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their rivals Fatah, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas could tell themselves that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a rising regional power, once Israel&#39;s closest Muslim ally, has taken up the cause of Hamas; just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Hamas members gloat and say the Islamist crescent curves around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the Hezbollah militia holds sway, to Syria, where Islamist-leaning rebels can topple Bashar El Assad, and as far as Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And most importantly, on Israel&#39;s southern flank, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time for Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood are cousins of Hamas, and their leaders rely more easily on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important player that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, Israel&#39;s hardliners will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been re-boxed.
The missile interception system called Iron Dome proved its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles were destroyed.
The Israelis are going to be able to rest easy - for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America renews its unwavering support; and many European countries have blamed Hamas for being behind the latest wave of violence.
But above all, Israel has prospered, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who completely ignored the peace process.
Although rocket attacks from Gaza have killed around 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared suicide bombings, not least thanks to the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements which continue to expand despite their illegality under international law.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party merged with an even more hawkish party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, has a winning streak.
Why coddle those pesky Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they ruled the West Bank, wouldn&#39;t they launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It&#39;s best to keep them behind that wall and hit them as soon as they stick their heads out.
Perhaps the hardliners will prevail; but the Arab Spring may change that.
Even if the Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere dislike Israel, their priority will be to tackle the problems in their own countries.
Israel&#39;s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments fix their economies.
Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to secure a ceasefire, which bodes well -- and could be the start of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, denying the Palestinians their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is bound to explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories - much like the bus that exploded in Tel- Aviv this week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are exacerbating this problem as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions into Gaza every two or three years to ring out Hamas will have a diplomatic price.
Both sides need to be pushed by those on the outside.
The answer remains the one advocated by reasonable people on either side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with Israel ceding territory in exchange for security.
One hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will provide an opportunity for outsiders to champion this cause.
Egypt, which must now work to end the flow of arms to Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is better placed than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state according to 1967 borders with land swaps and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute much more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the upcoming proposal for a pseudo-state at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has every interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
During his first term, he did not present his own peace plan.
Back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to establish one.
It&#39;s a very narrow view.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This requires a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Laws for plain cigarette packs come into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of diseased organs cover the dark green packets that are all identical, regardless of brand
This law, which came into force in Australia, is a world first, the logos and colors have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrific photos of diseased organs and depictions of children and babies whose illnesses have been caused by their parents&#39; smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, as of this Saturday, is the brand name, printed in small type on all the packages.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
Australia&#39;s federal government said the aim was to deter young people from smoking by removing all glamorous portrayal.
Studies have shown that if people didn&#39;t start smoking until age 26, there&#39;s a 99% chance they&#39;ll never start.
“Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco companies through their brand image,” Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek said, citing studies that found for example that children associated the crown of a logo with a princess.&quot;
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on multinational profits, other countries are considering a similar move.
The tobacco industry lobbied against this law.
Tobacco companies said it would kick-start black market trade, which will provide easier access to cheaper cigarettes.
&quot;Adverse consequences will flow from this legislation,&quot; said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said the law boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to hide the ugly packaging, had risen sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain&#39;s Imperial Tobacco , Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost in the High Court of Australia.
Ha said Zico has sold 6,000 to wholesalers and is awaiting restocking.
For us, business is good.
The only downside, experts say, is the popularity of social media and the demographic targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws banning TV advertising, sports sponsorship and requiring retailers to conceal cigarettes, tobacco marketing is now available online.
Australia has banned web advertising by local companies and sites, but it cannot prevent foreign sites from doing so.
“If you work in tobacco marketing and only have a small storefront left to promote your products, the internet is the go-to place,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman has noticed an increase in contributions from some average citizens in favor of brands on social media like YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
We have to ask ourselves, is this a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes and went to the trouble of making a video, or is this an agency-orchestrated marketing campaign?
British American Tobacco Australia said the industry is focused on the new regulations rather than marketing.
The industry has gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge these new court rulings - these countries have told the WHO that the trade is being unfairly disadvantaged, although none of these countries has had significant trade with Australia.
A WTO decision should be taken in the course of 2013.
Plibersek said the government has held discussions with other countries regarding similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to mandate warning photos on packaging in 2001.
Now, these warnings are present in 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are currently under consideration in England, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia remain oblivious to these photos.
The pictures don&#39;t bother me.
I ignore them.
&quot;You take a cigarette and you put the packet away,&quot; Victor El Hage said when buying a packet that featured a photo of a tumor in his mouth.
To be frank, the only reason that will make me quit is my little girl.
James Yu, manager of &#39;King of the Pack tobacconist&#39; in central Sydney, said the uniformity of packaging made it difficult to arrange packs on shelves.
“Before, it took me an hour to unload a parcel, now it takes me four hours,” Yu said.
&quot;The government had only to ban them once and for all and we would have said OK, it&#39;s good, we stop and we put the key under the door&quot;, he added, raising his arms to the sky.
In a constantly connected world, it can be good to be bored.
I spent five hours at an airport over Thanksgiving because our plane had mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
Therefore, I had enough time to reflect on the theme of boredom.
I won&#39;t lie to you.
Spending half a day in an airport waiting for a flight is boring enough, even when you have books, magazines and iPhones to distract you (not to mention the duty-free shops).
But increasingly, some academics and child development experts are praising boredom.
It&#39;s perfectly normal for us - and our children - to get bored once in a while, they say.
This forces the brain to take interesting paths, even nurturing creativity.
And since most of us are constantly in front of several types of screens, we no longer know the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yes.
And no.
But I will come back to it.
First of all, like many people, I thought boredom was a fairly recent phenomenon, especially since we have more free time.
But that&#39;s not the case, says Peter Toohey, professor of Greco-Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of &quot;Boredom: A Lively History&quot; (Yale University Press, 2011).
“Boredom goes way back,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii are Latin graffiti that evoke boredom, they date back to the first century.
Then there is the definition we give to boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined, and debated, in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After scanning numerous publications and submitting the idea to a discussion group of around 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience of &quot;wanting to do something, but not being able to engage in a satisfying activity.&quot;
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task although they would like to.
With apathy, he says, there is no urge to do anything.
What is at the heart of boredom, he said, is “the interruption of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly.”
Boredom can strongly resemble depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while the two may be linked, people who are bored tend to think the problem is with the environment or the world, while people who are depressed think the problem is with them.
Sometimes we think we&#39;re bored when it&#39;s actually a problem with concentration.
In their study, &quot;The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention&quot;, which was published in the journal &quot;Perspectives on Psychological Science&quot; in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an older experience in which participants listened on tape to the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard from the next room too loud an unrelated TV broadcast, others just heard the TV broadcast, and the third group did not didn&#39;t hear the soundtrack at all.
Those who heard the TV at a low level said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had difficulty concentrating, but did not know why, and attributed the concentration problem to boredom.
When you&#39;re trying to focus on a difficult or time-consuming task, an interruption in attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and the one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you&#39;re doing a boring task, &quot;like looking at things on an assembly line, music can help keep you from getting bored.&quot;
In fact, he says, now we know that when we squirm or doodle, these gestures, often seen as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay physically more alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to fidget learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” Professor Fenske said.
We are all bored at one time or another - the delay of my plane flight, a speaker with a monotonous voice, a particularly boring movie.
But some people are more likely to be bored than others.
To measure this, researchers developed the &quot;Boredom Prone Scale&quot; in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as, &quot;Many of the tasks I do are repetitive and monotonous&quot;, and &quot;I have so many interests that I don&#39;t have time to do them all. .&quot;
Using such a scale, the researchers found that boys tend to be bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, and in particular need many and varied stimulations. .
But in general, teenagers are quickly jaded.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of individual and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers said they were bored at school and while doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they weren&#39;t in school.
In contrast, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know if boredom percentages today, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he added that he knows that &quot;teenage is a time when boredom reaches its peak&quot;, not least because children and teenagers don&#39;t have much control over what they want to do.
If I rest my question: is boredom good for you?
Sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can cause people to take absurd physical risks, gamble or abuse certain substances to pass the time, as studies show.
By contrast, many philosophers and writers point to a connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
&quot;Boredom is the brain&#39;s way of letting you know you should be doing something else,&quot; said NYU psychology professor Gary Marcus.
But the brain doesn&#39;t always know what the most appropriate thing to do is.
If you are bored and use that energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
But if you watch TV, it will make you happy in the short term, but not in the long term.
So if your child is bored and you give them an iPad, they won&#39;t be bored, but they won&#39;t have learned self-care or self-regulation, says Professor Fenske.
And &quot;this self-regulation moves from one situation to another,&quot; he says.
Your child isn&#39;t just learning how to be entertained, they&#39;re gaining more self-control in other areas.
I don&#39;t think we should glorify boredom.
Just as I don&#39;t think we should criticize it either.
Feeling comfortable outside of the constant buzz of business and technology is what we should be aiming for.
Professor Eastwood agrees on this point.
&quot;We need to be bored more often, but boredom stirs a sharp, frantic desire to be connected to something meaningful,&quot; he said.
According to him, what people are looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy the downtime.
&quot;In an environment where we&#39;re constantly overstimulated,&quot; he added, &quot;it&#39;s hard to find ways to get into something when the noise stops.&quot;
In Colorado, no guidelines for new marijuana law
Anthony Orozco, 19, a college student and soccer player in Colorado, is charged with something that will soon become legal in his state: possession of marijuana pellets and a pipe used to smoke them.
Mr. Orozco said that one day in September, he and some friends were in a car in Lamar, in the middle of the fields, near the border with Kansas, when they were arrested.
After the police officer found the marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco received a summons for possession of the drug and equipment that could be used for its consumption - minor offenses, each carrying a fine of 100 $ - and an appearance date.
“We are being treated like criminals,” Mr. Orozco said.
But is it one?
During the weeks of uncertainty following Colorado&#39;s vote to legalize the consumption of small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the response to hundreds of cases involving low drug use depends more on location than law .
Here and in the state of Washington, which has adopted a similar measure, hundreds of offenses involving the use of marijuana have been dismissed.
Police departments have stopped charging adults 21 and older with underage possession of marijuana as the law comes into effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in more conservative Colorado precincts have called for expediting existing marijuana cases and are continuing to charge those who possess it.
Meanwhile, several towns from suburban Denver to the western mountains are currently voting to prevent state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their neighborhoods.
&quot;Things are changing so quickly that I don&#39;t know what the future holds,&quot; said Aurora Police Chief Daniel J. Oates, east of Denver.
Washington state regulators also have a lot of questions.
They are seeking guidelines on how to set up a licensing system, authorizing them to produce, manufacture, distribute and sell - before the December 1, 2013 deadline.
They say that Colorado, like it or not, is ahead of most states when it comes to marijuana regulations, first in therapeutic use and now in personal use.
&quot;Colorado has a more regulated market, and is a good indicator,&quot; said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Control Board.
But no place or system, Smith acknowledges, can do more than suggest what works.
&quot;There&#39;s no real precedent we could build on,&quot; he said.
Washington&#39;s law, called I-502, takes effect Dec. 6, leaving a one-year loophole during which the licensing system will still not exist, while possession of marijuana will be legal. .
Meanwhile, practical questions remain unanswered: how to balance the state mandate that guarantees appropriate access to licensed marijuana and prohibits the establishment of cannabis businesses within 30 km of a school , park, playground or nursery.
&quot;There will be no places more difficult than urban areas to set up a licensed business selling cannabis, especially in the Seattle metro area,&quot; said Ben Livingston, a spokesperson for the Center for Cannabis Legalization, a newly formed research group.
On Nov. 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates sent an email to his officers announcing that the City Attorney would no longer prosecute people 21 and older who possess small amounts of marijuana, and that the police should stop charging people for this type of offense &quot;with immediate effect.&quot;
Chief Oates said police will enforce new court orders that regulate the activity of those who grow medical marijuana, and he will continue to prosecute drug traffickers and dealers.
In Weld County, in northern Colorado, the &quot;district attorney&quot; (Attorney of the Republic), Ken Buck, embodies a stricter vision.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to handle marijuana possession cases, primarily to pressure users to get detoxified.
Currently, 119 people are charged with possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, but many of them face other charges.
&quot;Our office has an obligation to prosecute these individuals who have committed an offense which, at the material time, was a recognized offence,&quot; Buck said.
Reactions were complicated even in rural places like Mesa County, where voters rejected the initiative in favor of restricted marijuana use.
Police in Grand Junction, the county&#39;s largest city, are no longer bringing adults to court for possession of restricted amounts.
County District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported the move, but also decided not to drop all marijuana possession cases.
&quot;I don&#39;t feel like I&#39;m wasting my time continuing to enforce the law until it changes,&quot; he said.
Although 55 percent of voters in Colorado supported the measure, providing an appropriate legal and governmental framework for the personal use of marijuana is not easy.
And the mixed reactions that have been seen in different US cities highlight the deep ambivalence among local officials regarding the legalization of marijuana.
&quot;It&#39;s a cultural barrier&quot; with the prosecution officials, said Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents those charged with marijuana use and who speaks as a local spokesperson for the &quot;National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws&quot;.
&quot;They&#39;ve spent a good part of their lives prosecuting people for using marijuana, so they have a hard time accepting that it&#39;s legal,&quot; he said.
As the first states to treat restricted marijuana use on the same level as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are set to become a case for drug legalization.
As advocates and state officials plan for a new frontier of legalized sales, they anxiously await direction from the federal government, which still views the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Marijuana legalization advocates are hoping the Justice Department will relent.
Despite some high-profile arrests of medical marijuana patients and vendors, the federal government has mostly allowed medical marijuana businesses to operate in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
While it&#39;s true that the police are unlikely to break down doors to seize small packets of drugs, it&#39;s a safe bet that they will oppose the licensed businesses selling marijuana for personal use allowed by the new laws. said Kevin A. Sabet, a former political adviser to the Obama administration.
Many Colorado cities did not wait for federal authorities to act.
Long before the votes, some local governments approved moratoriums on the creation of new marijuana businesses, even if it is only a one-year delay.
Last week, the town of Montrose was granted a 6-month moratorium, and is expected to impose the ban next week.
“We don&#39;t want to end up in a situation where somebody is given a license and then we end up with a federal problem,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
