Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied and kicked out of Oxford because I was a Tory (conservative).
It is not just today&#39;s students who are attacked for their opinions.
As far back as I can remember, I have always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and my older brother studied in what was for me an eminent place of learning, a sort of modern-day Greek amphitheater that stimulates the two pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
Yet two weeks after moving to Worcester College in the late 80s to study history, I decided to pack my bags, sparking the first scandal of my life.
My dad broke down and started crying.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I left this university because I objected to undergraduates having sex in the room next to mine.
Author AN Wilson joked that I left after being forced to drink from chipped cups.
The truth was less funny.
I fled.
Yes, I fled because I had been intimidated and constantly bullied.
Not because of my rather outrageous name, nor because I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one and only reason, and in this cradle of so-called knowledge, I was the victim of racist and barbaric behavior: my late father, Woodrow Wyatt, was a very influential adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a Conservative Party supporter.
Why bring up this today, you will say.
Well, recent studies have revealed that a new generation of center-right students are experiencing the same kind of persecution.
Such is the growing and institutionalized hatred of Tory students at Oxford that last week some of them demanded protection of their rights, along with those of gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College&#39;s Student Hall (JCR) said they were &quot;often isolated, personally attacked and felt unwanted&quot; because of their political views.
They want there to be a representative on the university&#39;s Committee for Equal Opportunities so that their opinions can be expressed freely.
Their situation has not been made easier by the recent BBC Two documentary &#39;Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right&#39;, about student politics. , which portrayed the &quot;Tories&quot; as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
We discovered in particular the student Joe Cooke, former president of the “Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA)”, who travels in a Rolls-Royce, wears a silver suit and travels with a cane with a chrome head.
At other universities, conservative students say they are being treated as scapegoats for the implementation of the tuition hike.&quot;
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told a Sunday newspaper &quot;there is a growing left-wing bias at universities.
People think we&#39;re like the Bullingdon Club without even having met us.&quot;
Samuel Roberts, 21, a Corpus Christi history student who moved a motion for more protection, says such a climate is &quot;uncomfortable&quot;, and Stephanie Cherill, 19, president of the OUCA, says that there has been a deterioration in the attitude of JCR members towards people who are centre-right.
“It constitutes an obstacle to the freedom of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of the members,” she said.
I was the only one to think so during my first weeks at Oxford.
I entered in September 1986, I was then 18 years old and paralyzingly shy.
The hatred of the Conservative Party was very virulent.
The previous year, the university had voted to refuse to grant Margaret Thatcher - a former student - an honorary title, because of the reduction in funding for graduate studies.
The atmosphere was charged with Stalinist vibrations.
From the first days of the welcome week, when the new students got to know each other and the teachers, I had a taste of what was to come next.
I discovered that the teachers not only participated in the sarcasm towards Tory students, but that they also took pleasure in it.
It was as if the politics of striking miners, privatization and the government&#39;s opposition to sanctions against apartheid in South Africa were carved into the wood of the classrooms.
The first sarcasm I received was about a translation into English of French texts from the 18th century, and I was not prepared for it.
&quot;Miss Wyatt&quot;, said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), &quot;please translate the first paragraph&quot;
I lost my footing.
Pitt, a short, pustular-faced man, was quick-tempered.
&quot;Do Thatcherists refuse to learn French or are they just stupid?&quot; he asked.
The other students laughed.
Tears burned my eyes.
&quot;I suggest you take French lessons in your spare time - well, if you&#39;re not too busy making friends,&quot; he snapped.
I returned to my room, inconsolable.
At dinner that night, I sat alone and then felt a light tap on my shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
&quot;I know who you are,&quot; he said, kindly.
I am afraid that is so.
Anyone suspected of being a Tory (conservative) is targeted.
It&#39;s hard enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it&#39;ll be even harder for you.
Most Tory youth claim to be Labour.
Later, at the local pub, I cowardly tried to hide.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Mrs Thatcher had said.
This ploy failed.
