The toughest job in the world: Kawah Ijen&#39;s human mules
For four euros, Indonesian volcano porters risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies on contact with the air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which altogether weigh nearly 70 kilos, he places them in two bamboo baskets which he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
It&#39;s only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters above sea level, but exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle&#39;s pace, keeping their balance and measuring their not so as not to stumble and fall over the precipice.
They know that one wrong step could cost them their life, as happened to a French tourist who fell to her death in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for each kilo of sulfur mined.
Once at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scales that a mining company has installed. a little below at 1,850 meters above sea level.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, we can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupiahs (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulphur.
She then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry since this mineral is very present in daily life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to whiten sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each one takes him 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but it saves him 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems like a pittance for such superhuman effort, it is triple what he would earn in the fields.
“The income of miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the porter who worked once as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not so difficult, but Anto returned close to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason which, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as brimstone: &quot;I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and brought her back to Java to convert to Islam&quot;.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he has spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but the brimstone has already started to make him foot the bill despite covering his face with a mask and wearing special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
This is the price he must pay to pursue his dream.
&quot;I&#39;m going to work for two more years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,&quot; he promises in more than acceptable English.
Busted by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the work of a mule.
He shares an unsanitary wooden hovel with other porters, gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop spurting out at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the midst of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater, lighting himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought for himself with his own money.
Some 400 porters load the sulfur baskets onto their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who are self-employed and paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not receive a penny of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) surcharge per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
&quot;This work is for beasts, not for humans,&quot; protests Madrusin, a portly 42-year-old porter who has worked at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since leaving middle school.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working &quot;as long as he can&quot;, because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18 years old.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke rising from the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from the serious illnesses... obviously add their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, 53-year-old Unainik can only load 50 kilos.
Every day he and his companions extract 15 tonnes of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse at Tamansari, 18 kilometers away via a weedy goat path.
&quot;I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life,&quot; Unainik says, opening his mouth wide, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of her five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
