The Unasur summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe tried several times to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially signaled that it would be released after the closing of the summit, then claimed that it would be published at any time on the Peruvian government&#39;s website.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists&#39; access to information about the summit was constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly with the message &quot;private session, audio restricted&quot; was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating between the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, Peru&#39;s presidency sent an email to the media with the &quot;final declaration&quot; of the summit, but it was President Humala&#39;s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American-Arab Countries (ASPA) Summit and, on this occasion, although it had been urgently requested by the press, it also did not broadcast the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, you can verify that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the obtaining of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment from the Court of The Hague which settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and said they would respect the decision of the ICJ to hear the arguments of both sides in the trial that Lima has brought against Santiago and which begins Monday in The Hague.
&quot;We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we bring today before this international court,&quot; said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
&quot;Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, international treaties and tribunals,&quot; President Piñera added, shaking hands with President Humala, alongside flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Pact of Bogota by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua, which she considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its ex-president Fernando Lugo, did not take part in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would take “important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits”.
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve &quot;cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and against international organized crime, actions for better accessibility to medicines, access to the Internet at low cost in the whole of South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters&quot;.
With a Europe in crisis, &quot;the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to glimpse a better future for our populations&quot;, concluded President Humala.
&quot;We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits&quot;, said said the Peruvian president during a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although it did not have no further details were given.
Likewise, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
&quot;We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations&quot;, from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, was another theme discussed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional appointment, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through of an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” President Santos said.
&quot;We are going to revise all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will require having a discussion with this country&quot;, he underlined.
&quot;I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we are going to settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,&quot; added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday, where they plan to witness the inauguration of that country&#39;s new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, within the framework of the summit, the bloc&#39;s defense ministers will meet beforehand to approve the Action Plan for the year 2013, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defense in the region. .
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country be suspended.
