Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth (Texas), became known worldwide for the main role of John Ross Ewing, better known as JR, in the television series &quot;Dallas&quot;, in which he embodied an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil tycoon JR Ewing on the television series &quot;Dallas&quot; became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as JR in a new season of &quot;Dallas,&quot; died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for the Warner Bros., home of &quot;Dallas&quot; production.
&quot;Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the ironic role he loved the most,&quot; the family said.
Larry&#39;s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on the Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, his publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
&quot;He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest,&quot; Gray said in a statement.
Doctors diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he admitted to drinking heavily for many years.
In 1995 he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and underwent a transplant.
Several years before &quot;Dallas&quot;, Hagman had made a name for himself on television as an ordinary guy in the series &quot;Jinny of my dreams&quot; broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, &quot;The Good Life&quot; (NBC, 1971-72) and &quot;Here We Go Again&quot; (ABC, 1973).
His film roles include critically acclaimed roles in &#39;The Band&#39;, &#39;Harry and Tonto&#39; and &#39;Primary Colors&#39;.
But it was thanks to his masterful portrayal of the deliciously detestable JR that Larry Hagman achieved his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan &quot;Who Killed JR?&quot;, coined to keep the suspense going around an emotionally charged episode in which Hagman&#39;s character is nearly murdered, has generated worldwide speculation and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record rating at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers were in front of their screens and made &quot;Dallas&quot; the second most-watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of &quot;MASH &quot; in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was JR&#39;s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. got her pregnant and then threatened to charge her with prostitution if she didn&#39;t leave town, but other people also had reason to assault her.
Hagman played Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest contractor and unfaithful husband who tried to commit his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
&quot;I know what it would take for an epitaph for JR,&quot; Hagman said in 1988.
It should read: &quot;Here lies Honest Citizen JR Ewing.&quot;
This is the only game he lost.
