And he is not the only professor to give courses on &quot;the end of the world&quot; this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course &quot;Media, Culture and the End of the World&quot;.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer what-if scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and explore how they compare with real-life examples.
&quot;I tried to educate my students on what was possible, probable, believable and impossible,&quot; Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled &quot;The End of the World&quot;.
&quot;We&#39;re adding &#39;2012&#39; to have the option of running the course again, in case the world doesn&#39;t go away,&quot; Professor Restall said.
Despite the &quot;imminent disaster&quot;, students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be taken the day before the Apocalypse, which leaves students no choice but to work &quot;until the very night of the supposed end of the world&quot;, a declared Restall.
The courses have proven to be quite popular.
